---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="About | Willy W."
  description="Who Willy W. is and how he builds real systems with an AI-native workflow."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <p class="kicker">about</p>
    <h1>I use AI like a small engineering team, then make the work prove itself.</h1>
    <p>
      I'm Willy, a self-taught builder and retail trader. I don't come from a software
      engineering background, and that's precisely what this site documents: what one
      motivated person can design, build, and ship by working with AI tools seriously
      instead of casually.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section aria-labelledby="work-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="work-title">How I work with AI</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-card">
      <p>
        Every system I ship goes through the same loop. Claude plans the architecture,
        challenges my assumptions, and reviews every change. Codex builds, one strictly
        scoped phase at a time, one clean commit each. Obsidian and plain markdown files
        keep the durable memory: specs, decisions, and status live in the repo, so any
        session (or any model) can pick up exactly where the last one stopped.
      </p>
      <div class="pipe">
        claude <span>(architect/review)</span> &rarr; codex <span>(build)</span> &rarr;
        obsidian <span>(memory)</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        The rules that make it work: two models so the author never reviews its own code,
        pre-agreed scope so nothing gets "helpfully" over-built, and independent
        verification so "it works" is demonstrated, not claimed. The full breakdown is in
        <a href="/blog/two-ai-dev-team/">the write-up</a> and on the
        <a href="/toolkit/">AI Toolkit</a> page.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="principles-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="principles-title">What I optimize for</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-card">
      <p>
        <strong>Evidence over conviction.</strong> My favorite project outcome so far is a
        strategy I killed with a pre-registered experiment before it cost anything.
        The <a href="/projects/prediction-market-backtester/">documented negative result</a>
        taught me more than a lucky win would have.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Safety before capability.</strong> The trading systems I build get risk
        engines, testnet-first rollouts, and keys that can't withdraw, so the worst case
        is decided in advance instead of discovered in production.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Files over vibes.</strong> Decisions get written down with their
        reasoning. Anything that matters survives the end of a chat session.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="background-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="background-title">Background</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-card">
      <p>
        Markets are where I learned to respect data. I trade as a retail investor, and the
        discipline that survives contact with a live market (position sizing, kill
        criteria, honest postmortems) turns out to transfer directly to building
        software with AI. If you want the specifics of what I've built, start with the
        <a href="/projects/">projects</a>; if you want how I think, start with the
        <a href="/blog/">writing</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
